    {
      "id": 141,
      "title": "LLM Router — Packaging, Versioning & Release Pipeline",
      "status": "done",
      "priority": "medium",
      "dependencies": [127],
      "details": "Package the entire LLM Router subsystem as a clean, modular internal crate or module that can be versioned and evolved independently while remaining tightly integrated with the CPU pipeline. Define a clear versioning strategy (semantic versioning or router-specific version tags) so that breaking changes, feature additions, and bug fixes are communicated consistently to consumers. Ensure the router can evolve without breaking the CPU pipeline, existing tools, or downstream skills by maintaining a stable public API surface and marking internal modules appropriately with Rust visibility rules.\n\nIntroduce feature flags that allow optional subsystems (telemetry collector, scenario simulator, debug/inspection tools, visualization JSON emitter) to be compiled in or out, enabling minimal or full-featured builds as needed. Integrate the router crate into the bot's Cargo workspace and build pipeline so that any change to router code triggers the full test suite. Add automated CI jobs that run on every commit touching router code, exercising unit tests, integration tests, golden-file regressions, performance benchmarks, and health/fallback verification.\n\nCreate a formal release checklist that must be satisfied before any router release: config schema validation, golden-file routing regression tests, performance benchmark assertions, health-check stability tests, fallback chain verification, and documentation updates. Document the release process, versioning rules, and API stability guarantees so that future maintainers can execute releases confidently. Plan for future extensibility such as router plugins or dynamic strategy loading while preserving the deterministic, side-effect-free contract of the core routing function.",
      "testStrategy": "CI integration tests that run on every router change. Versioning regression tests that verify public API stability across releases. Release pipeline validation that enforces the checklist. API stability checks using cargo-semver-checks or equivalent tooling.",
      "subtasks": [
        {
          "id": "141.1",
          "title": "Package router as modular crate with clear public/private boundaries",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Stable API surface, internal modules hidden."
        },
        {
          "id": "141.2",
          "title": "Define versioning strategy and semantic rules",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Semver or router-specific tags with clear policy."
        },
        {
          "id": "141.3",
          "title": "Add feature flags for optional subsystems",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Telemetry, simulator, debug tools, visualization."
        },
        {
          "id": "141.4",
          "title": "Integrate router into bot build and CI pipeline",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Automatic test runs on every router commit."
        },
        {
          "id": "141.5",
          "title": "Create release checklist and validation scripts",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Config, golden files, perf, health, fallback."
        },
        {
          "id": "141.6",
          "title": "Write release process and versioning documentation",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Step-by-step guide for future maintainers."
        },
        {
          "id": "141.7",
          "title": "Plan for future plugin / dynamic strategy extensibility",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Roadmap without breaking determinism."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 142,
      "title": "LLM Router — Metrics, Analytics & Long-Term Observability",
      "status": "done",
      "priority": "medium",
      "dependencies": [127],
      "details": "Design and implement a metrics and analytics subsystem that provides long-term visibility into the LLM Router's behavior and health. The subsystem must continuously track and aggregate key operational signals: backend selection frequency (per-backend counts and percentages), fallback rates (how often the primary choice is unavailable), override usage patterns (one-shot vs session vs persistent), complexity score distributions, end-to-end routing latency histograms and percentiles, GPU load and LAN latency patterns, backend health state transitions, and routing errors or anomalies.\n\nDefine a stable MetricsRecord struct that captures aggregated data for a given time window. Implement rolling windows at multiple granularities (1 minute, 5 minutes, 1 hour, 24 hours, 7 days) so operators can observe both short-term spikes and long-term trends. Add histogram and percentile tracking (P50, P95, P99) for latency and complexity scores, enabling SLO monitoring and performance regression detection.\n\nIntegrate the metrics layer with the existing structured logging and telemetry systems so that every routing decision contributes to the aggregate view without blocking the hot path. Collection must be low-overhead and fully asynchronous. Design a pluggable exporter architecture supporting local JSON files, SQLite, Prometheus, and future backends, allowing the same metrics data to feed multiple observability platforms.\n\nProvide a CLI/TUI command that displays real-time router metrics, current window aggregates, and recent trends. Ensure that from the router's perspective all metrics collection is deterministic: identical inputs produce identical routing decisions regardless of whether metrics are enabled. Plan for future enhancements such as anomaly detection, automatic alerting on unusual fallback rates, and adaptive routing strategies informed by historical data.",
      "testStrategy": "Unit tests for metrics aggregation, rolling windows, histograms, and percentile calculations. Integration tests for each exporter backend. Golden-file tests that capture known routing workloads and their expected MetricsRecord snapshots to prevent regression in analytics output.",
      "subtasks": [
        {
          "id": "142.1",
          "title": "Define MetricsRecord struct and aggregation schema",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Selection counts, fallbacks, overrides, latency histograms, health transitions."
        },
        {
          "id": "142.2",
          "title": "Implement rolling time windows (1m, 5m, 1h, 24h, 7d)",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "Efficient sliding-window aggregation with deterministic results."
        },
        {
          "id": "142.3",
          "title": "Add histogram and percentile tracking for latency and complexity",
          "status": "done",
          "details": "P50/P95/P99 support with bounded memory."
